- Fri 1 Feb 2019. Epidemiological situation report, DRC Ministry of Health
[in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=377ff1d6b7

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri dated 31 Jan 2019:
- Since the beginning of the epidemic, the cumulative number of cases is 763, of which 709 are confirmed and 54 are probable. In total, there were 471 deaths (417 confirmed and 54 probable) and 262 people healed.
- 168 suspected cases are under investigation.
- 4 new confirmed cases, including 1 in Katwa, 2 in Butembo, and 1 in Biena.
- 3 new deaths of confirmed cases, including 1 community death in Butembo, 2 deaths at Butembo CTE
- 3 new healed people, including 2 exits from Butembo CTE and Katwa CTE.

News of the response

Point of entry surveillance
- Epidemiological surveillance at entry points has adopted a new strategy in relation to the new response plan put in place. This strategy consists in making the entry points work [24 hours a day] with the support of the security services. To this end, surveillance at the points of entry has already identified 7 priority entry points (PRRP, Kanyabayonga, Mukulia, Kasindi Foner, Foner Komanda, Ituri Bridge, and Mabakese), including 4 -- namely, PRRP, Kanyabayonga, Mukulia, and Kasindi Foner -- that are already implementing [24 hour a day] screening with police support. It should be noted that all these priority points are control points, except Fonner Kasindi, and are an integral part of the 77 entry points that are functional. These priority points will be increased later on the basis of the migratory flow and the expansion of the epidemic.
- This new strategy and growth, compared to those who refuse screening, which is decreasing from 0-9% to 1% on average, has improved the point-of-entry surveillance that has already reached 30 million screened travelers.
- Screening at entry points aims to stop the circulation or spread of Ebola from one medium to another. To achieve this objective, port-of-entry services conduct human observation to detect travelers with clinical signs related to Ebola virus disease, use temperature sensing to detect persons with more than 38 deg C/100.4 deg F, and record all travelers to identify the epidemiological link between their home environment and their destination environment.
- Once a person meets the case definition, they are considered alert and automatically placed in isolation for investigation. If the investigation validates this case, it is transferred to the Ebola treatment center for further investigation by laboratory or biological analysis.
- Entry points are roads or any road that leads to another country, while the checkpoint is internally between agglomerations.

Vaccination
-----------
- Since the beginning of vaccination on 8 Aug 2018, 71 449 people have been vaccinated.

--
