[3] Assessment after 6 months
- Fri 1 Feb 2019. Why Congo's Ebola outbreak still going strong
[AP News, edited]
https://www.apnews.com/8a99202b716c43f6aad6b831ecfe0521
[Byline: Cara Anna]

The Ebola outbreak in eastern Congo, the 2nd-deadliest in history, marks 6 months on Fri [1 Feb 2019] and is moving toward the major border city of Goma, a development that would greatly complicate any hope of stopping the virus' spread in the unstable region.

This may be the most challenging Ebola outbreak ever. Health workers face the threat of attack from rebel groups and resistance from frightened communities. A highly mobile population produced 2 scares in the past week alone: the discovery of an infected, wide-ranging young trader led to vaccinations in a new, 3rd province near the South Sudan border. And 2 contacts of Ebola victims slipped away and were found in the capital of neighboring Uganda, free of the virus.

And yet this outbreak has seen a number of advances, including the widespread use of an experimental Ebola vaccine and a clinical trial of experimental treatments. Health workers say conditions have improved from the devastating West Africa outbreak a few years ago, when some patients were housed by the dozens in sweltering tents and used buckets for toilets.

Congo's health ministry reports 759 cases, including 705 confirmed cases and 414 confirmed deaths. Ebola is spread via infected bodily fluids, including those of the dead.

More than 70 000 people have received the experimental Ebola vaccine, whose efficacy has yet to be determined. Some people who have received the vaccine have still fallen ill. As concerns about the vaccine stockpile grow, drug maker Merck last week said it will ship another 120 000 doses or so to Congo by the end of this month [February 2019].

Women and children make up a worrying number of cases, including more than 160 children under age 18. More than 280 children have been orphaned, the UN children's agency says.

Cases are still emerging without any link to confirmed ones, a sign of how difficult it is to track the virus in a dense and often wary population in a region with little infrastructure. Millions of people have been checked for Ebola at border posts with Rwanda and Uganda, which the World Health Organization says are at "very high" risk.

"People don't yet know what the disease is," Dr. Brian D'Cruz with Doctors Without Borders said this week, a startling comment 6 months into an outbreak in which health teams have hustled to combat misinformation as soon as cases appear in communities. One survivor, Aline Kahindo Mukandala, recounted for the medical charity how she and others had thought Ebola patients at treatment centers were simply zipped into body bags on arrival.

"No, the foreigners are not here to steal our organs," another survivor tells communities as he helps the International Committee of the Red Cross speak out in churches, markets, and schools.

Ebola response workers have been attacked, both by rebels and community members. Other people fearing Ebola try to flee. Each suspension of virus containment efforts because of a security threat can lead to a jump in new cases.

The Ebola outbreak is now a day's drive from Goma, a city of more than 1 million people on the heavily traveled border with Rwanda. The UN says coordination of the outbreak response is already being moved to Goma, where nearly 2000 frontline workers have received vaccinations in preparation.

Some health experts have warned that the infectious disease could defeat efforts to contain it and become a permanent threat in the turbulent region, which would force already struggling health clinics to adapt their operations. Ebola response workers aim to keep a 2 m [6.6 ft] distance from those infected and ideally wear head-to-toe protective gear. How local workers would assist with childbirths, treat malaria, and carry out other daily activities among North Kivu province's estimated 7 million people remains to be seen.

And were Ebola to become entrenched there, international efforts to stop the disease would need continued resources and funding, while neighboring countries would need to make border health checks permanent to prevent the importation of cases.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Kunihiko Iizuka

[There are several points raised in this report that are worth discussing. One is the statement that "some people who have received the vaccine have still fallen ill." There has been little, if any, information on the Merck vaccine efficacy, likely because we are still in the middle of the outbreak. The case numbers remain low with limited spread suggesting it is working well. But one would anticipate that individuals who are vaccinated after already being infected may not be protected depending on time since infection. It would be good to read more on this. Perhaps vaccination post-infection plus antiviral therapy could be more protective. And it's possible that severity of illness may be diminished by the vaccine even when it is delivered post-infection.

Also, the continued suspicion the communities have of the Ebola treatment centers is somewhat astounding after they have observed their family, friends, and neighbors suffer from Ebola disease without having had any exposure to the treatment centers. Changing these false perceptions is clearly a major challenge that social scientists can best address.

Ebola outbreaks are so devastating because of the disease's impact on children, especially on top of loss of family members to the violent conflict in the region. Cases include "more than 160 children under age 18. More than 280 children have been orphaned, the UN children's agency says." It will take a long time for communities to recover from this terrible loss.

How the DRC would manage were Ebola to become endemic in the region, as raised in this report, must be considered in order to preemptively prepare for that possibility. Healthcare centers would need to be re-designed and many more frontline workers vaccinated. But the authorities do appear to be optimistic the DRC is on the right path to stopping transmission before this would occur. - Mod.LK]

- Sat 2 Feb 2019. WHO is "optimistic" about Ebola control
[Radio Okapi, online trans., edited]
https://www.radiookapi.net/2019/02/02/actualite/sante/rdc-loms-assez-optimiste-sur-le-controle-debola

Six months into the Ebola outbreak in the DRC, efforts to stop the spread of the virus are "encouraging," Dr. Matshidiso Moeti, director of the WHO Regional Office for Africa, said in Geneva today.

"What worked well was public health measures such as training of infection prevention and control agents in health centers," Moeti told reporters for the World Health Organization.

Dr. Matshidiso Moeti also emphasized closer engagement with communities, especially women and religious groups, as well as other health measures such as contact tracing alongside the use of newer tools in the fight against Ebola.

Faced with the press, Dr. Moeti posted her optimism about the evolution of the disease and the change observed on the ground "with the help of local community leaders."

What she sees as a "strategy of success" has led to a situation "almost under control in Beni, Mangina, Komanda, and Oicha" 6 months after the beginning of the epidemic.

In these 1st 2 epicentres of the health crisis, the combination of different actions contributed to the situation. "We have learned lessons from the epidemic in West Africa, including the importance of engaging with local communities to avoid distrust and suspicion," she added, especially because the setting up of an effective response sometimes faces many difficulties, including the very unstable security context or certain reluctance of the population, to which the WHO teams must adapt.

For WHO, it is therefore a question of continuing their efforts with communities to try to reduce fears about the care provided by health personnel.

"Despite ongoing challenges related to the security and distrust of local communities that impact response measures, our teams are continuing the fight," said Moeti. In this respect, she mentions a gradual improvement in the face of these resistances.

The UN Health Agency realizes that "insecurity continues to be a factor" affecting the system put in place by WHO and its partners. However, the situation is "relatively quiet compared to the pre-election period," which had resulted in the postponement of the presidential election in Beni, said Dr. Mike Ryan, assistant director general for emergencies, returning from the area. Many armed groups had carried out attacks.

According to Dr. Ryan, the teams are operational in all areas even though in some communities they need "special security measures" to work.

"This is the case in Biena, Kalunguta, Kayina, Kyondo, Mangurujipa, or Komanda, places where the WHO and its partners need escort or special protection," said Dr. Ryan, recalling that teams are in all "areas of active transmission of the virus."

"But we thank the forces of MONUSCO that allow us, with his escorts, to continue working in this environment," he said while emphasizing the indispensability of "this safety umbrella" of UN peacekeepers.

"A relatively high number of cases has been reported in recent weeks, mainly because of the epidemic in the health zone of Katwa," said the WHO in a statement released Thu 31 Jan 2019. Nearly 178 suspected cases are under investigation, and of the 7 new confirmed cases, 6 are in Katwa and 1 in Butembo.

To better control the disease, more than 70 000 people have been vaccinated in 28 health zones, spread among 4 provinces of the Democratic Republic of Congo. And 350 were treated with new drugs widely used for the 1st time. "The response also consists of the border work the DRC shares with its neighbors," said Dr Moeti.

Neighboring countries are also on the alert. Several thousand health personnel were vaccinated, including 2600 in Uganda alone.

About 200 specialists have been deployed to assist these governments. The priority in the DRC is now to prevent the epidemic in the west of the affected region from spreading further, especially since Ebola is not the only health problem facing the DRC. The country faces diseases such as cholera, measles, polio, monkey pox virus, and malaria.

"Not to mention the health needs of the humanitarian crisis in other provinces. This puts a lot of pressure on the health system in general, "added Dr. Moeti.

Moreover, in Beni, the epicenter of Ebola, WHO is also involved in the fight against malaria. A campaign targeting 300 000 people in this area provided free distribution of impregnated mosquito nets and anti-malaria drugs.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[This is an optimistic report. Read Crof's [Crawford Kilian's] blog for a less optimistic assessment: https://crofsblogs.typepad.com/h5n1/2019/02/ebola-a-worrying-trend.html. - Mod.LK]

- Fri 1 Feb 2019. Top WHO official sees progress in grueling fight against Ebola outbreak
[STAT News, abridged, edited]
https://www.statnews.com/2019/02/01/top-who-official-sees-progress-in-grueling-fight-against-ebola-outbreak/
[Byline: Helen Branswell <@HelenBranswell>]

... So far, 18 health zones in 2 provinces in northeastern Congo -- North Kivu and Ituri -- have reported cases. That part of the country is engulfed in a decades-long conflict that has significantly hampered efforts to stop spread of the virus.

While moving about can be difficult -- unsafe -- for the outbreak response workers, people in the area, which is populous, are highly mobile. That has allowed for a frustrating phenomenon in which someone who gets infected in one area will travel to another to evade detection or to be with family, igniting transmission in a new location. On more than one occasion, a place where Ebola transmission had been stopped has experienced renewed spread sparked by the arrival of another infected person.

Earlier this week, the Congolese ministry of health reported on the case of a traveling trader who contracted the disease in Katwa and then returned to his home in Watsa, more than 300 miles [483 km] -- and more than nine hours by road -- away. Ryan said a response team quickly moved in and vaccinated the man's contacts and their contacts to try to prevent the virus from taking off once again.

For much of the autumn, the major transmission hot spot was a city of more than 200 000 people called Beni. But after months of effort -- and the administration of more than 20 000 doses of an experimental Ebola vaccine made by Merck -- the outbreak there appears to be on the verge of ending, Ryan said.

The city had gone nearly 3 weeks without a case, but recently 6 new infections there have been reported. All were connected to known chains of transmission, said Ryan, who described the outbreak in Beni as being on "that bouncy road to zero."

Katwa -- and the neighboring city of Butembo -- have been harder nuts to crack, with members of the community refusing in many cases to cooperate with the response teams. But Ryan said efforts to get community leaders and civil society groups engaged in the containment fight are bearing fruit.

The number of alerts -- tips from people that someone might have Ebola -- is on the rise. And people sick with the virus are going to treatments centers earlier in their illness. Where a few weeks ago most people waited 8 or 10 days to go, many are now showing up 2 or 3 days after developing symptoms. That's critical: cases cared for in treatment centers are more likely to survive. It also lowers the risk they'll transmit the virus to family members.

"Even in Katwa, where there is intense transmission, there are hopeful signs," said Ryan.

Still, as the grueling outbreak enters month 7, response leaders aren't taking anything for granted. "A tremendous amount has been achieved. But we're not done. And we're nowhere close to being done," Ryan said. "And we're going to be working in Katwa for weeks to come to suppress transmission."

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

